","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1335–before 1373":"circa 1335–vóór 1373","1322–1365":"1322–1365","1335–1373":"1335–1373","1338–1372":"1338–1372","1347–1413":"1347–1413","1333–1373":"1333–1373","1311–1373":"1311–1373","1314–Female":"1314–Overleden","1373":"1373","1372":"1372","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1314":"1314","1413":"1413","1347":"1347","1335":"1335","1311":"1311","1333":"1333","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","about 1335":"circa 1335","before 1373":"vóór 1373","Brackley, South Northamptonshire Borough, Northamptonshire, England":"Brackley St Peter, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"about 1335–before 1373":"about 1335–before 1373","1322–1365":"1322–1365","1335–1373":"1335–1373","1338–1372":"1338–1372","1347–1413":"1347–1413","1333–1373":"1333–1373","1311–1373":"1311–1373","1314–Female":"1314–Deceased","1373":"1373","1372":"1372","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1314":"1314","1413":"1413","1347":"1347","1335":"1335","1311":"1311","1333":"1333","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","about 1335":"about 1335","before 1373":"before 1373","Brackley, South Northamptonshire Borough, Northamptonshire, England":"Brackley St Peter, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Holand","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Holland  .","Norwegian: habitational name from about twenty farmsteads so named, composed of Old Norse <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, field’, denoting a high-lying farm."],"variants":[{"name":"Holland","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Danish, Norwegian, Swedish, French, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from <i>Holland</i>, a province of the Netherlands.","English: habitational name from Downholland or Upholland (Lancashire), Hulland (Derbyshire), the Parts of Holland, one of the three administrative subdivisions of Lincolnshire, any of the four places called Hoyland (southern Yorkshire), and possibly Great and Little Holland (Essex). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","English: habitational name either from Hoeland (Farm) in Bury (Sussex), or from Holland's Barn in Albourne (Sussex). The placename in Bury has the same etymology as in 1 above, while the placename in Albourne may derive from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert de Holand V was born about 1335, in Northamptonshire, England, his father, Robert de Holand IV, was 26 and his mother, Margery Heaton, was 23. He had at least 1 son. He died before 1373, in his hometown, and was buried in Brackley St Peter, Northamptonshire, England."},"et":{"about 1335–before 1373":"umbes 1335–enne 1373","1322–1365":"1322–1365","1335–1373":"1335–1373","1338–1372":"1338–1372","1347–1413":"1347–1413","1333–1373":"1333–1373","1311–1373":"1311–1373","1314–Female":"1314–Surnud","1373":"1373","1372":"1372","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1314":"1314","1413":"1413","1347":"1347","1335":"1335","1311":"1311","1333":"1333","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","about 1335":"umbes 1335","before 1373":"enne 1373","Brackley, South Northamptonshire Borough, Northamptonshire, England":"Brackley St Peter, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1335–before 1373":"noin 1335–ennen vuotta 1373","1322–1365":"1322–1365","1335–1373":"1335–1373","1338–1372":"1338–1372","1347–1413":"1347–1413","1333–1373":"1333–1373","1311–1373":"1311–1373","1314–Female":"1314–Kuollut","1373":"1373","1372":"1372","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1314":"1314","1413":"1413","1347":"1347","1335":"1335","1311":"1311","1333":"1333","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","about 1335":"noin 1335","before 1373":"ennen vuotta 1373","Brackley, South Northamptonshire Borou